 </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="Question_3_3_18">
    <title> Problem 18</title>
    <p>

    Let <m>p</m> be a prime such that <m>p \nmid b.</m>

    The arithmetic progress is <m>a+kb</m> where <m>k \in \mathbb{Z}.</m>. Our goal is to produce the values of <m>k</m> such that <m>p|a+kb.</m>

    Since <m>p \nmid b</m>, there exist integers <m>r</m> and <m>s</m> such that <md number="yes">
        pr+bs=1.
    </md>

    Let <m>n_k=kp-as</m>. This is the value we'll use for <m>k</m> in the arithmetic progression:

    <md>
        <mrow>a+kb \amp = a+(kp-as)b</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = a-asb+kpb</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = a(1-sb)+kpb.</mrow>
    </md>

    Clearly <m>p|kpb</m>. Also <m>p|1-sb</m> since  <m>pr+bs=1</m>.  This gives the desired result: <m>p|a+kb.</m>
    Notice that each of these constructed terms are <m>p</m> apart: <md>
        ((k+1)p-as)-(kp-as)=p.
    </md>
    
    If <m>b</m> is odd, then <m>2 \nmid b</m> so every other term is divisible by <m>2.</m>

    </p>

  </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="Question_3_3_24">
    <title> Problem 24</title>
    <p>
        Except for <m>p=2</m> and <m>p=3</m>, all primes are congruent to either <m>1</m> or <m>5</m> modulo 6.
        Suppose <m>p</m> is the first of a twin pair.  That is, <m>q=p+2</m> is the second. 
    </p>
        
        <p> If <m>p\equiv 1 \pmod{6}</m>, then <m>q\equiv 3 \pmod{6}</m> which is only prime if <m>q=3</m>. 
        </p>
          <p>  Thus, if  <m>p</m> is the first of a twin prime pair, <m>p\equiv 5 \pmod{6}</m>.  The second prime <m>q\equiv 1 \pmod {6}.</m> Then <md>
            <mrow>pq-2 \amp \equiv 3 \pmod{6}</mrow>
        </md> which, again, is prime only if <m>pq-2=3.</m> But this would give <m>pq=5</m> which is impossible.
    </p>

    <p>
        This leaves <m>p=3</m> and <m>q=5</m>. Check that <m>pq-2=13</m> which is indeed prime.  The only twin prime pair such that <m>pq-2</m> is also prime is <m>p=3</m> and <m>q=5.</m>
        
    </p>
    </subsection>
        
